month = 3
day = 5

# We can use a loop to add 365 or 366 days to the start date until we reach the desired count.
current_date = date(year, month, day)
while count > 1:
    if current_date.year % 4 == 0 and (current_date.year % 100 != 0 or current_date.year % 400 == 0):
        # leap year
        current_date += timedelta(days=366)
    else:
        # non-leap year

    count -= 1

# The answer formatted with %m/%d/%Y is
ans = current_date.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

import calendar

# Thanksgiving is on the fourth Thursday of November
def thanksgiving_date(year):
  cal = calendar.Calendar(firstweekday=calendar.SUNDAY)
  # get all the Thursdays in November
  nov_thursdays = [day for day in cal.itermonthdates(year, 11) if day.weekday() == calendar.THURSDAY]
  # get the fourth Thursday
  fourth_thursday = nov_thursdays[3]
  return fourth_thursday

def get_thanksgiving_date(year):
    # November 1st of the year
    november_1st = date(year, 11, 1)

    november_1st_weekday = november_1st.weekday()
    # Thursday of the first full week of November

from datetime import date, timedelta

# On May 9th, 2017 Jane bought 40 eggs. She ate one per day. Today she ran out of eggs.
start_date = date(2017, 5, 9)
days_passed = (date.today() - start_date).days
eggs_left = 40 - days_passed

# date 24 hours later
date_24_hours_later = date.today() + timedelta(days=1)
# The answer formatted with %m/%d/%Y is
ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

from datetime import date, timedelta

# On May 9th, 2017 Jane bought 40 eggs. She ate one per day. Today she ran out of eggs.
start_date = date(2017, 5, 9)
days_since_start = (date.today() - start_date).days + 1
eggs_left = 40 - days_since_start

# date 24 hours later
date_24_hours_later = date.today() + timedelta(days=1)
# The answer formatted with %m/%d/%Y is
ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

from datetime import date, timedelta
from dateutil.relativedelta import relativedelta

# Today she ran out of eggs. What is the date 24 hours later?
date_24_hours_later = end_date + timedelta(days=1)

# The answer formatted with %m/%d/%Y is
ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

# On May 9th, 2017 Jane bought 40 eggs. She ate one per day. Today she ran out of eggs. What is the date 24 hours later in MM/DD/YYYY?
# Jane bought 40 eggs on May 9th, 2017. The last egg was eaten on June 17th, 2017 (40 days later)
last_day_of_eggs = date(2017, 6, 17)
# 24 hours later
date_24_hours_later = last_day_of_eggs + relativedelta(hours=24)
# The answer formatted with %m/%d/%Y is
ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

# On May 9th, 2017 Jane bought 40 eggs. She ate one per day. Today she ran out of eggs. What is the date 24 hours later in MM/DD/YYYY?

# Number of days between May 9th, 2017 and today
days_since_purchase = (date.today() - date(2017, 5, 9)).days
# Number of eggs left
eggs_left = 40 - days_since_purchase
# If there are no eggs left, the date 24 hours later is simply tomorrow
if eggs_left == 0:
    ans = (date.today() + timedelta(days=1)).strftime('%m/%d/%Y')
else:
    # Otherwise, we need to calculate the date when the last egg was eaten
    last_egg_date = date.today() - timedelta(days=eggs_left)
    # The date 24 hours later is then simply the next day
    ans = (last_egg_date + timedelta(days=1)).strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

# On May 9th, 2017 Jane bought 40 eggs. She ate one per day. Today she ran out of eggs. What is the date 24 hours later in MM/DD/YYYY?
# Jane bought 40 eggs on May 9th, 2017. Today is 24 hours after the last egg was eaten.

days_left = 40 - days_since_eggs
if days_left <= 0:

    date_24_hours_later = date.today() + timedelta(days=1)
else:
    # If Jane still has eggs left, the date 24 hours later is the date when she will run out of eggs
    date_24_hours_later = date.today() + timedelta(days=days_left)

ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

ans = date_24_hours_later.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')
